1. Introduction to PySpark — PySpark is Python plus Apache Spark, built for processing data too big for pandas. You spin up a SparkSession, load data into a DataFrame, and everything is lazy — transformations like .filter() only build a plan, and nothing actually runs until an action like .show() triggers it. RDDs were the older, lower-level way of doing this before DataFrames took over.
2. Setting Up a Spark Session — Beyond the basic SparkSession.builder.appName(...).getOrCreate(), you can tune it with .config() calls: executor/driver memory and core counts for resource control, shuffle partition counts for join/aggregation performance, event logging and checkpoint directories for debugging, JDBC settings for database connections, and things like the broadcast-join size threshold for performance tuning.
3. Reading & Writing Files — There's one universal pattern for both directions: spark.read.format(...).option(...).load(path) to read, and df.write.format(...).option(...).mode(...).save(path) to write. It works across CSV, JSON, Parquet, ORC, Hive tables, and JDBC databases — you just swap the format and options. Save modes control what happens if the destination already exists: overwrite, append, ignore, or error. CSV/JSON/Parquet also have shortcut methods (spark.read.csv(...), df.write.parquet(...)) so you don't always need the full .format() syntax. Read modes (PERMISSIVE, DROPMALFORMED, FAILFAST) control how corrupt records are handled.
4. Working with CSV Files — Deep dive into CSV-specific options: header, inferSchema, custom delimiters (sep), null-value markers, date formats, and error-handling modes when reading; header inclusion, save mode, delimiter, and compression (gzip, snappy, etc.) when writing.
5. Working with JSON Files — Similar deep dive for JSON: reading line-delimited JSON by default, or multi-line/pretty-printed JSON with multiLine=True; schema inference with an optional sampling ratio to speed things up; the same corrupt-record modes as CSV; and on the write side, compression and partitioning output into subfolders by column value (e.g. by year).
6. Referring to Columns — Five ways to point at a column: plain string names ("age"), dot notation (df.age), the col() function (best for dynamic/variable column names), bracket notation (df["age"], needed for names with spaces/special characters), and lit() for injecting constant values into expressions.
7. Selecting Columns — Covers select() for picking columns, withColumn() for adding/computing new ones, alias() and withColumnRenamed() for renaming, expr() for SQL-style expressions inside a select, dropping unwanted columns, running actual SQL via a temp view, selecting a dynamic list of columns, and drilling into nested struct fields (like address.city).
8. Filtering Data — filter() and where() are interchangeable. You can combine conditions with &, |, ~; filter with SQL-style strings; check list membership with isin(); match text patterns with startswith(), endswith(), like(), and regex via rlike(); and handle missing data with isNull()/isNotNull(). You can also just register a temp view and run a WHERE clause in plain SQL.
9. Grouping Data — groupBy() mirrors SQL's GROUP BY. Pair it with .agg() and functions from pyspark.sql.functions (imported as F by convention) like F.sum, F.avg, F.count, F.countDistinct to compute multiple metrics per group at once, aliasing each result column.
10. Joining Data — Supports inner, left, right, outer/full, cross, left_semi (inner join but keeps only left-side columns), and left_anti (left rows with no match on the right) joins. You can join on one column, multiple columns, or a custom condition (useful when key names differ), and combine multiple join conditions with &/|.
11. Pivoting Data — Turns row values into columns using groupBy().pivot().agg(). You can restrict which values become columns (avoiding overly wide results), run multiple aggregations at once, and watch out for nulls where no data exists for a group/pivot combination, plus the shuffle cost on large data.
12. Handling Nulls & Missing Data — na.fill() fills nulls with defaults (different values per column if you want), dropna() removes rows with nulls (with how="all" or a subset of columns to target), na.replace() swaps out specific values (not just nulls), and where()/filter() give conditional control instead of blanket dropping.
13. Date & Time Functions — to_date/to_timestamp for parsing strings into dates, date_format for formatting them back to strings, current_date/current_timestamp for now, year/month/dayofmonth/dayofweek/weekofyear for extracting parts, datediff/add_months/date_add/date_sub for date math, and trunc/date_trunc for rounding down to a period boundary.
14. Math Functions — Basic arithmetic works directly with + - * / % on columns. Built-in functions cover rounding (round, ceil, floor, abs), exponents/logs (exp, log, log10, pow, sqrt), and trig (sin, cos, tan).
15. String Functions — Concatenation (concat, concat_ws), substrings and regex extraction (substring, regexp_extract), search/replace (instr, regexp_replace), case conversion (upper, lower, initcap), trimming/padding (trim, ltrim, rtrim, lpad, rpad), and length/similarity (length, levenshtein).
16. Window Functions #1 — A Window spec (partitionBy + orderBy) lets you run aggregates like sum/avg/min/max "over" a window to get running totals or per-group stats without collapsing rows the way groupBy does. Ranking functions rank (leaves gaps on ties), dense_rank (no gaps), and row_number (always unique) assign positions within each partition.
17. Lead and Lag — lead(col, offset, default) and lag(col, offset, default) pull a value from a future or past row within the same window — handy for period-over-period comparisons, trend/change detection, and filling in defaults when there's no next/previous row.
18. Rows Between — rowsBetween(start, end) on a window lets you define exactly which rows count relative to the current one, using Window.unboundedPreceding, Window.currentRow, Window.unboundedFollowing, or numeric offsets. This is how you compute running totals, moving averages (e.g. a 3-row window), or sums that exclude the current/future rows.
